1.4.2 Class declaration and constructor
export default class GameScene extends Phaser.Scene {
  constructor() {
    super({ key: 'GameScene' });
  }
This single line packs in six distinct JavaScript concepts. Here is each word:
export makes GameScene available outside this file. ES modules are isolated by default — nothing defined in GameScene.js is visible elsewhere unless explicitly exported. Without export, the import GameScene from './GameScene.js' line in main.js would fail with a reference error.
default marks this as the file’s primary export. A file can have many named exports but only one default export. The distinction changes the import syntax: a default export is imported without curly braces (import GameScene from './GameScene.js'), while a named export would require them (import { GameScene } from './GameScene.js'). Using default here signals to any reader of this file: “this class is the point of this file.”
class declares a JavaScript class — a named blueprint for creating objects. A class groups related data and behavior together under one name. Before ES6 (2015), the same thing was accomplished with constructor functions and prototype chains, which worked but were verbose and error-prone. The class keyword is cleaner syntax for the same mechanism.
GameScene is the name of the class. By convention, class names use PascalCase (each word capitalized, no underscores). This name is what you use to instantiate the class with new GameScene(), and it is what Phaser uses in error messages when something goes wrong inside the scene.
extends sets up inheritance: GameScene is declared as a subclass of Phaser.Scene. Inheritance means GameScene gets everything Phaser.Scene already knows how to do, without having to rewrite it. Think of it as a family relationship — Phaser.Scene is the parent; GameScene is the child. The child adds its own behavior on top of the parent’s.
Phaser.Scene is the parent class, defined inside the Phaser library. It contains the machinery every scene needs: the lifecycle system that calls preload(), create(), and update() at the right times; and the plugin system that attaches this.physics, this.add, this.cameras, this.input, and all the other tools you use inside a scene. By extending Phaser.Scene, you inherit all of that infrastructure instantly. If you tried to write a scene class that did not extend Phaser.Scene, none of those tools would exist on this.
The constructor runs once when Phaser instantiates the class (which happens when new Phaser.Game(config) registers your scene list). It calls super({ key: 'GameScene' }), which passes a config object up to the parent class constructor. The key is the scene’s internal name — the string you use to switch to it from anywhere else in your code:
this.scene.start('GameScene');   // from another scene
this.scene.restart();            // restart this scene
this.scene.pause('GameScene');   // pause it
If you don’t call super() in a subclass constructor, JavaScript throws a ReferenceError before the constructor body even runs. It is a hard requirement for any class that uses extends.

Quiz: Why extend Phaser.Scene?
If you removed extends Phaser.Scene from the class declaration, leaving just class GameScene { ... }, what would go wrong?

 Nothing — extends Phaser.Scene is purely a style choice.  Phaser would refuse to load the game and crash on startup.  this.physics, this.add, this.input, and the other scene tools would be undefined, because those are inherited from Phaser.Scene’s constructor — every line that uses them in create() would throw a TypeError.  The game would run but in slow motion, since gravity defaults to zero without a scene parent. Check Answer







1.4.3 Why all methods must live inside the class
constructor(), create(), update(), and the helpers genRect and genCircle must all be defined inside the class body — not outside it as standalone functions. There are two reasons.
Reason 1: this only refers to the scene instance inside a method. Inside a class method, this refers to the specific instance of the class — the live scene object with all its Phaser tools attached. If you moved create() outside the class as a regular function, this would either be undefined (in strict mode) or the global window object. Every line that says this.physics, this.add, this.input, or this.player would fail.
Reason 2: Phaser looks for these methods by name on the instance. When Phaser launches a scene, it effectively does:
const scene = new GameScene();
scene.create();        // called once when the scene starts
scene.update(time, delta);  // called every frame
If create and update are not on the instance — meaning they are not defined as methods of the class — Phaser simply does not call them. The game would start but nothing would appear. Phaser does not raise an error for a missing create() or update(); it just skips calling them if they are not found.
The same logic applies to genRect and genCircle: they use this.make.graphics(), which only works because they are class methods with access to the scene instance. As standalone functions, they would have no way to reach Phaser’s scene API.

Quiz: Static vs dynamic bodies
The ground and platforms are created with physics.add.staticImage / staticGroup, but the player uses physics.add.sprite (dynamic). What is the functional consequence of choosing static versus dynamic?

 Static bodies are invisible to the physics engine — they only exist for rendering.  Static bodies are not affected by gravity, velocity, or collisions — they stay fixed in place. Dynamic bodies (like the player) have their position updated every frame based on velocity and gravity, and are pushed out of the way when collisions are resolved.  Static bodies use less memory but cannot participate in colliders or overlaps.  Dynamic bodies are rendered as circles; static bodies are rendered as rectangles. Check Answer







1.4.4 When you would have other classes
Our game has only GameScene, but a more developed game typically has several classes. Some extend Phaser classes; others are plain JavaScript classes used as helper objects.
Additional scene classes are the most common. Each major “screen” in the game becomes its own scene:
class BootScene   extends Phaser.Scene { }  // shows a logo, loads minimal assets
class MenuScene   extends Phaser.Scene { }  // title screen, play button
class GameScene   extends Phaser.Scene { }  // the level itself
class PauseScene  extends Phaser.Scene { }  // pause overlay, layered on top of GameScene
class GameOver    extends Phaser.Scene { }  // death screen, score, retry button
Custom game object classes let you give enemies, bullets, or pickups their own self-contained logic:
class Enemy extends Phaser.GameObjects.Sprite {
  constructor(scene, x, y) {
    super(scene, x, y, 'enemy');
    this.health = 3;
    this.speed  = 80;
  }
  update() {
    // enemy-specific movement AI here
  }
}
Because Enemy extends Phaser.GameObjects.Sprite, it is a real Phaser sprite with physics, animations, and all the normal sprite properties — plus any custom properties and methods you add to it.
Plain helper classes handle logic that has nothing to do with Phaser specifically — managing save data, tracking level progression, or controlling audio:
class ScoreManager {
  constructor() { this.score = 0; this.highScore = 0; }
  add(points) { this.score += points; }
  save() { localStorage.setItem('highScore', this.score); }
}
This class does not extend anything — it is just a clean way to group related state and behavior. You would instantiate it in a scene’s create() and store it as this.scoreManager.


1.4.5 Canvas dimensions
const W = this.scale.width;
const H = this.scale.height;
this.scale is Phaser’s Scale Manager. .width and .height return the current canvas dimensions (800 and 500, as set in main.js). Storing them in W and H avoids repeating this.scale.width throughout create() and makes it easy to position objects relative to the canvas size rather than hardcoding pixel values.


1.4.6 Generating textures procedurally
this.genRect('ground',   W,   32, 0x4caf50);
this.genRect('platform', 160, 18, 0x8b6914);
this.genRect('plat_sm',  120, 18, 0x8b6914);
this.genRect('player',   32,  48, 0x5c9ded);
this.genCircle('coin',   10,      0xffd700);
To understand why these calls are necessary, you need to understand how Phaser draws anything at all.
Phaser’s sprite and image game objects don’t draw shapes — they draw textures. A texture is a bitmap image (a grid of pixels) that lives in the GPU’s memory and is identified by a string key. When you write this.physics.add.sprite(100, H-80, 'player'), the third argument is not a description of the shape — it is a key that Phaser looks up in its internal texture cache. If the key doesn’t exist in the cache yet, you get a blank 32×32 white square as a placeholder (Phaser’s built-in missing-texture indicator).
Normally you populate the texture cache in preload() by loading image files:
preload() {
  this.load.image('player', 'assets/player.png');
}
We have no image files. So instead, we create textures programmatically right at the start of create(), using our helper methods. Each genRect and genCircle call draws a colored shape into an off-screen Graphics object and then “bakes” it into a named texture entry in the cache via generateTexture(). By the time the first this.physics.add.staticImage(...) call runs, every key it needs — 'ground', 'platform', 'plat_sm', 'player', 'coin' — already exists in the cache and is ready to use.
This is why the five genRect/genCircle calls appear at the very top of create(), before any game object is created. Swap their order with the ground or player setup, and those objects would get the white placeholder texture instead.
The colors are hexadecimal values: 0x4caf50 is a medium green (ground), 0x8b6914 is brown (platforms), 0x5c9ded is blue (player), 0xffd700 is gold (coin).

Quiz: Texture cache ordering
Suppose you moved the line this.genRect('player', 32, 48, 0x5c9ded) to the very bottom of create(), AFTER this.player = this.physics.add.sprite(100, H - 80, 'player'). What happens when the game runs?

 A JavaScript error is thrown and the game refuses to start.  The player sprite renders as a blank 32×32 white square — Phaser looked up the key 'player' in the texture cache, didn’t find it yet, and used the built-in missing-texture placeholder.  Phaser delays sprite creation until every genRect call completes, so it works exactly the same.  The blue player appears, but jumping stops working because the physics body is not registered. Check Answer







1.4.7 Ground
const ground = this.physics.add.staticImage(W / 2, H - 16, 'ground');
staticImage creates a physics-enabled image with a static body — it has a collider but never moves. The position (W / 2, H - 16) places it centered horizontally, 16 pixels from the bottom edge. Since the ground texture is 32 pixels tall and Phaser positions objects by their center, this puts the bottom edge of the ground exactly at the bottom of the canvas.


1.4.8 Platforms
this.platforms = this.physics.add.staticGroup();
this.platforms.create(200, 350, 'platform');
this.platforms.create(500, 250, 'platform');
this.platforms.create(350, 160, 'plat_sm');
A staticGroup is a container for static physics objects that are managed together. Adding a collider between the player and the group automatically checks against every member of the group — you don’t need a separate collider for each platform. The three platforms form a staircase pattern: left at y=350, middle at y=250, top at y=160.


1.4.9 Player
this.player = this.physics.add.sprite(100, H - 80, 'player');
this.player.setCollideWorldBounds(true);
add.sprite creates a dynamic physics sprite — one whose body is affected by gravity and velocity each frame. The player starts near the bottom-left of the canvas. setCollideWorldBounds(true) prevents the player from leaving the canvas edges; without it the player could walk off the sides or fall through the floor of the world.


1.4.10 Colliders
this.physics.add.collider(this.player, ground);
this.physics.add.collider(this.player, this.platforms);
These two lines wire up solid physics collisions. Each frame, Phaser checks whether the player’s body overlaps with the ground or any platform. If it does, it resolves the overlap by pushing the player back to the surface. This is what makes the player land and stand instead of passing through objects.


1.4.11 Coins and overlap
this.coins = this.physics.add.staticGroup();
this.coins.create(150, H - 60, 'coin');
this.coins.create(480, H - 60, 'coin');
this.coins.create(200, 320,    'coin');
this.coins.create(500, 220,    'coin');
this.coins.create(350, 130,    'coin');

this.physics.add.overlap(this.player, this.coins, (_player, coin) =&gt; {
  coin.destroy();
  this.score++;
  this.scoreText.setText('Score: ' + this.score);
});
Five coins are placed: two near the ground and one above each platform. Unlike platforms, coins use overlap instead of collider. The player passes through coins rather than landing on them. When an overlap is detected, the callback fires — the coin is destroyed (removed from the scene), the score counter increments, and the score text is updated. The callback receives two arguments: the player and the specific coin that was touched. The player argument is prefixed with _ to signal it is intentionally unused.

Quiz: Collider vs Overlap
Suppose we changed this.physics.add.overlap(this.player, this.coins, ...) to this.physics.add.collider(this.player, this.coins, ...) (keeping the same callback). The player’s first encounter with a coin would look different — how?

 No visible difference — collider and overlap behave identically, the callback fires either way.  The player would physically collide with the coin and be pushed away, as if the coin were a tiny platform — before the callback’s coin.destroy() removes it. Using overlap lets the player pass straight through without any physical reaction.  The game would crash, because collider is only for two dynamic bodies and coins are in a static group.  The callback would never fire — collider does not support callbacks. Check Answer







1.4.12 Score text
this.score = 0;
this.scoreText = this.add.text(16, 16, 'Score: 0', {
  fontSize: '20px', color: '#ffffff', fontFamily: 'monospace'
}).setDepth(1);
this.add.text places a text object at pixel position (16, 16) — top-left corner. The style object controls appearance. setDepth(1) ensures the text renders on top of all other game objects (which default to depth 0). this.score is a plain JavaScript number stored on the scene instance so the overlap callback can access and increment it.


1.4.13 Hint text
this.add.text(W / 2, 16, '← → to move   ↑ or Space to jump', {
  fontSize: '13px', color: '#aaaacc', fontFamily: 'monospace'
}).setOrigin(0.5, 0).setDepth(1);
This is a static label — it is never updated, so there is no need to save a reference to it. setOrigin(0.5, 0) shifts the text’s anchor point to its horizontal center, top edge. Combined with x = W / 2, this centers the text at the top of the screen. The default origin is (0, 0) (top-left corner), so without setOrigin, the text would start at the center and extend to the right.


1.4.14 Input setup
this.cursors = this.input.keyboard.createCursorKeys();
this.wasd = this.input.keyboard.addKeys({
  left:  Phaser.Input.Keyboard.KeyCodes.A,
  right: Phaser.Input.Keyboard.KeyCodes.D,
  jump:  Phaser.Input.Keyboard.KeyCodes.W
});
createCursorKeys() returns a pre-built object with keys for the four arrow keys plus Space and Shift. addKeys() maps arbitrary keys to named properties on a new object — here A, D, and W are mapped to left, right, and jump. Both objects are stored on the scene so update() can read them every frame. Setting up input in create() (not update()) is correct — you register the key bindings once, then poll their state repeatedly.


1.4.15 update() — Reading input state
const body    = this.player.body;
const onFloor = body.blocked.down;

const left  = this.cursors.left.isDown  || this.wasd.left.isDown;
const right = this.cursors.right.isDown || this.wasd.right.isDown;
const jump  = Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.cursors.up)
           || Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.cursors.space)
           || Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.wasd.jump);
update() runs every frame. The first thing it does is read the current input state. body.blocked.down is true when the player’s physics body is resting on a surface — this is used to prevent jumping in mid-air.
isDown is true on every frame a key is held. JustDown is true only on the single frame the key transitions from up to down. Using JustDown for jumping is essential: without it, holding the jump key would apply upward velocity on every frame for as long as the key is held, launching the player off the screen.

Quiz: JustDown versus isDown
For moving left, the code uses this.cursors.left.isDown. For jumping, it uses Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.cursors.up). Why the inconsistency?

 They are interchangeable — the author simply mixed styles for variety.  JustDown only works on arrow keys, while isDown works on all keys.  Movement is a continuous action — we want isDown to apply velocity every frame the key is held. Jumping is a one-shot action — JustDown fires on the single frame of the initial keypress, so holding the jump key doesn’t apply upward velocity repeatedly and launch the player into orbit.  JustDown is faster than isDown, and we want jumping to feel more responsive. Check Answer







1.4.16 update() — Movement and jumping
if (left)       body.setVelocityX(-220);
else if (right) body.setVelocityX(220);
else            body.setVelocityX(0);

if (jump && onFloor) body.setVelocityY(-550);
Movement is controlled by setting velocity directly each frame. This is the simplest possible movement model — there is no acceleration or deceleration. When no key is pressed, velocity is explicitly zeroed; without this the player would slide indefinitely since arcade physics has no built-in friction.
The jump condition requires both a JustDown event AND onFloor being true. Setting velocityY to -550 fires the player upward (negative Y is up in Phaser’s coordinate system). Gravity defined in main.js (gravity.y: 600) then pulls the player back down over subsequent frames.


1.4.17 Helper methods — genRect and genCircle
genRect(key, w, h, color) {
  const g = this.make.graphics({ add: false });
  g.fillStyle(color);
  g.fillRect(0, 0, w, h);
  g.generateTexture(key, w, h);
  g.destroy();
}

genCircle(key, radius, color) {
  const size = radius * 2;
  const g = this.make.graphics({ add: false });
  g.fillStyle(color);
  g.fillCircle(radius, radius, radius);
  g.generateTexture(key, size, size);
  g.destroy();
}
These are not methods Phaser knows about or calls — they are private utility methods you defined on the class to avoid repeating the same five-line pattern five times. Every time you need a new colored shape as a texture, you call one of them. The only reason they exist as separate methods (rather than being inlined into create()) is that the pattern repeats and giving it a name makes the code at the top of create() easier to read at a glance.
Both helpers follow the same five-step pattern:

this.make.graphics({ add: false }) — creates a temporary Graphics object, which is Phaser’s imperative drawing API (like an HTML Canvas context). The add: false option prevents it from appearing in the scene’s display list — it exists purely as a drawing tool in memory, invisible to the player.
fillStyle(color) — sets the fill color for all subsequent draw calls on this Graphics object.
fillRect / fillCircle — draws the shape at position (0, 0) within the Graphics object’s local coordinate space.
generateTexture(key, w, h) — this is the critical step. It rasterizes everything drawn on the Graphics object into a pixel buffer and registers it in Phaser’s texture cache under key. After this line, any Phaser game object can use key as its texture string, and the GPU has a copy ready to render.
g.destroy() — frees the temporary Graphics object from CPU memory. The texture it generated stays in the GPU cache for the lifetime of the game; only the drawing tool used to create it is discarded.

genCircle draws the circle at center (radius, radius) because fillCircle takes center coordinates as its first two arguments, and the texture canvas is radius * 2 pixels on each side. This places the circle exactly centered in the texture with no clipping at the edges.
The connection back to create() is direct: when you see:
this.genRect('player', 32, 48, 0x5c9ded);
// ... later ...
this.player = this.physics.add.sprite(100, H - 80, 'player');
The string 'player' is the thread that connects them. genRect registers it in the texture cache; add.sprite retrieves it from the cache. Remove the genRect call and the sprite renders as a blank white rectangle.

2.2 The full file
Here is the complete GameScene.js for Chapter 2. Everything added on top of Chapter 1 is discussed section by section below.
import * as Phaser from 'phaser';

export default class GameScene extends Phaser.Scene {
  constructor() {
    super({ key: 'GameScene' });
  }

  create() {
    const W = this.scale.width;
    const H = this.scale.height;

    // Textures
    this.genRect('ground',   W,   32, 0x4caf50);
    this.genRect('platform', 160, 18, 0x8b6914);
    this.genRect('plat_sm',  120, 18, 0x8b6914);
    this.genRect('player',   32,  48, 0x5c9ded);
    this.genRect('enemy',    28,  28, 0xff4444);
    this.genCircle('coin',   10,      0xffd700);

    // Ground
    const ground = this.physics.add.staticImage(W / 2, H - 16, 'ground');

    // Platforms
    this.platforms = this.physics.add.staticGroup();
    this.platforms.create(200, 350, 'platform');
    this.platforms.create(500, 250, 'platform');
    this.platforms.create(350, 160, 'plat_sm');

    // Player
    this.player = this.physics.add.sprite(100, H - 80, 'player');
    this.player.setCollideWorldBounds(true);

    this.physics.add.collider(this.player, ground);
    this.physics.add.collider(this.player, this.platforms);

    // Coins
    this.coins = this.physics.add.staticGroup();
    this.coins.create(150, H - 60, 'coin');
    this.coins.create(480, H - 60, 'coin');
    this.coins.create(200, 320,    'coin');
    this.coins.create(500, 220,    'coin');
    this.coins.create(350, 130,    'coin');
    this.totalCoins = 5;

    this.physics.add.overlap(this.player, this.coins, (_player, coin) =&gt; {
      if (this.gameOver) return;
      coin.destroy();
      this.score++;
      this.scoreText.setText('Score: ' + this.score);
      if (this.score === this.totalCoins) {
        this._endGame('You Win!', 0x2e7d32);
      }
    });

    // Enemy — patrols on top of the middle platform
    this.enemy = this.physics.add.image(440, 227, 'enemy');
    this.enemy.body.setAllowGravity(false);
    this.enemy.body.setImmovable(true);

    this.tweens.add({
      targets: this.enemy,
      x: 560,
      duration: 1400,
      yoyo: true,
      repeat: -1,
      ease: 'Sine.easeInOut'
    });

    this.physics.add.overlap(this.player, this.enemy, () =&gt; {
      this._endGame('Game Over', 0xb71c1c);
    });

    // Score & hint
    this.score = 0;
    this.gameOver = false;
    this.scoreText = this.add.text(16, 16, 'Score: 0', {
      fontSize: '20px', color: '#ffffff', fontFamily: 'monospace'
    }).setDepth(1);

    this.add.text(W / 2, 16, '← → to move   ↑ or Space to jump   R to restart', {
      fontSize: '13px', color: '#aaaacc', fontFamily: 'monospace'
    }).setOrigin(0.5, 0).setDepth(1);

    // Input
    this.cursors = this.input.keyboard.createCursorKeys();
    this.wasd = this.input.keyboard.addKeys({
      left:  Phaser.Input.Keyboard.KeyCodes.A,
      right: Phaser.Input.Keyboard.KeyCodes.D,
      jump:  Phaser.Input.Keyboard.KeyCodes.W
    });
    this.rKey = this.input.keyboard.addKey(Phaser.Input.Keyboard.KeyCodes.R);
  }

  update() {
    if (Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.rKey)) {
      this.scene.restart();
      return;
    }

    if (this.gameOver) return;

    const body    = this.player.body;
    const onFloor = body.blocked.down;

    const left  = this.cursors.left.isDown  || this.wasd.left.isDown;
    const right = this.cursors.right.isDown || this.wasd.right.isDown;
    const jump  = Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.cursors.up)
               || Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.cursors.space)
               || Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.wasd.jump);

    if (left)       body.setVelocityX(-220);
    else if (right) body.setVelocityX(220);
    else            body.setVelocityX(0);

    if (jump && onFloor) body.setVelocityY(-550);
  }

  _endGame(message, color) {
    if (this.gameOver) return;
    this.gameOver = true;

    this.physics.pause();
    this.tweens.killAll();

    const W = this.scale.width;
    const H = this.scale.height;

    this.add.rectangle(W / 2, H / 2, W, H, 0x000000, 0.55).setDepth(2);

    this.add.rectangle(W / 2, H / 2, 360, 90, color, 1).setDepth(3);
    this.add.text(W / 2, H / 2 - 8, message, {
      fontSize: '32px', color: '#ffffff', fontFamily: 'monospace', fontStyle: 'bold'
    }).setOrigin(0.5).setDepth(4);
    this.add.text(W / 2, H / 2 + 22, 'press R to restart', {
      fontSize: '14px', color: '#eeeeee', fontFamily: 'monospace'
    }).setOrigin(0.5).setDepth(4);
  }

  genRect(key, w, h, color) {
    const g = this.make.graphics({ add: false });
    g.fillStyle(color);
    g.fillRect(0, 0, w, h);
    g.generateTexture(key, w, h);
    g.destroy();
  }

  genCircle(key, radius, color) {
    const size = radius * 2;
    const g = this.make.graphics({ add: false });
    g.fillStyle(color);
    g.fillCircle(radius, radius, radius);
    g.generateTexture(key, size, size);
    g.destroy();
  }
}

2.5 The win condition
this.totalCoins = 5;

this.physics.add.overlap(this.player, this.coins, (_player, coin) =&gt; {
  if (this.gameOver) return;
  coin.destroy();
  this.score++;
  this.scoreText.setText('Score: ' + this.score);
  if (this.score === this.totalCoins) {
    this._endGame('You Win!', 0x2e7d32);
  }
});
Three additions to the Chapter 1 coin callback:
this.totalCoins = 5 — storing the target score as scene-level state. Hardcoding 5 inside the callback would work, but naming it makes the intent clear and makes it easy to change later if you add more coins.
if (this.gameOver) return; — a guard against double-firing. After _endGame pauses physics, most body movement stops — but the physics world still resolves any active overlaps on the frame the game ends. Without this guard, a player who touches an enemy while standing on a coin could trigger both the lose and win callbacks in sequence. The guard says: once the game is over, ignore any further coin pickups.
if (this.score === this.totalCoins) — the actual win check. After incrementing the score and updating the text, check whether the player has collected everything. Using === (strict equality) is the safe default; Phaser scores are always integers, so there is no risk of a NaN or string comparison going wrong.

2.7 The R key and restart

2.7.1 Binding the key in create()
this.rKey = this.input.keyboard.addKey(Phaser.Input.Keyboard.KeyCodes.R);
addKey (singular) is the simpler cousin of addKeys (plural) from Chapter 1. It registers a single key and returns a Key object that exposes .isDown and works with JustDown just like the arrow keys and WASD.


2.7.2 Handling it in update()
update() {
  if (Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.rKey)) {
    this.scene.restart();
    return;
  }

  if (this.gameOver) return;

  // ... rest of update ...
}
Two important structural details.
The R check comes first, before the gameOver guard. If R were checked after if (this.gameOver) return, then R would stop working the moment the game ended — which is exactly when you want it to work. Putting it first means R works any time: mid-game, after a win, after a loss.
this.scene.restart() tears down the current scene completely and reinitializes it. Every game object is destroyed, every texture is regenerated, create() runs again from scratch, and the scene starts over at frame one. The player is back at the starting position, all coins are present, the enemy is patrolling, the score is zero, gameOver is false.
return; after restart is critical. Once restart() has been called, the current update() call is still running — Phaser doesn’t interrupt it mid-function. Without the return, the rest of update() would execute against a scene that is in the middle of being torn down, throwing undefined errors when it tries to read this.player.body. Returning immediately prevents that.


2.7.3 JustDown vs isDown
The same reasoning as jumping in Chapter 1: JustDown fires exactly once when the key is first pressed. If we used isDown here, holding R for a few frames would trigger multiple restarts in rapid succession — each tearing down and rebuilding the scene — and the game would never stabilize.

2.8 The _endGame method
_endGame(message, color) {
  if (this.gameOver) return;
  this.gameOver = true;

  this.physics.pause();
  this.tweens.killAll();

  const W = this.scale.width;
  const H = this.scale.height;

  this.add.rectangle(W / 2, H / 2, W, H, 0x000000, 0.55).setDepth(2);

  this.add.rectangle(W / 2, H / 2, 360, 90, color, 1).setDepth(3);
  this.add.text(W / 2, H / 2 - 8, message, {
    fontSize: '32px', color: '#ffffff', fontFamily: 'monospace', fontStyle: 'bold'
  }).setOrigin(0.5).setDepth(4);
  this.add.text(W / 2, H / 2 + 22, 'press R to restart', {
    fontSize: '14px', color: '#eeeeee', fontFamily: 'monospace'
  }).setOrigin(0.5).setDepth(4);
}

2.8.1 The underscore prefix
_endGame starts with an underscore by convention. In JavaScript there is no enforced private-method mechanism on classes (short of # private fields, which have stricter semantics). An underscore is a soft signal to readers: “this method is an internal helper, not part of the class’s public interface. Phaser does not call it, and you should not call it from outside this class.”


2.8.2 Re-entry guard
if (this.gameOver) return;
this.gameOver = true;
Sets the flag immediately, before doing any work. Any subsequent call to _endGame on the same scene instance will exit early. This pattern — check-the-flag-then-set-the-flag — is how you make a function idempotent (safe to call more than once).


2.8.3 Freezing the world
this.physics.pause();
this.tweens.killAll();
this.physics.pause() stops the physics simulation: no gravity, no collision resolution, no velocity integration. Every dynamic body freezes in place. The player stops falling, the enemy stops patrolling. Crucially, update() still runs — it’s only the physics step in each tick that is paused. This is why the R key still works: update() still fires, it still checks the R key, it still calls this.scene.restart().
this.tweens.killAll() removes every active tween from the tween manager. Without this, physics.pause() would stop the physics engine from applying the tweened position — but the tween itself would keep writing enemy.x = whatever on every frame, fighting against the paused physics. killAll makes sure that doesn’t happen.


2.8.4 The overlay
this.add.rectangle(W / 2, H / 2, W, H, 0x000000, 0.55).setDepth(2);
this.add.rectangle(x, y, width, height, color, alpha) is the simplest Phaser game object for drawing a solid shape — you don’t need a texture or a Graphics object. Here it creates a full-canvas black rectangle at 55% opacity, dimming everything beneath it.
Depth matters. Phaser draws objects in order of their depth property (defaulting to 0). Everything the player interacted with during the game — platforms, coins, the enemy — is at depth 0. The score text is at depth 1. The dimming overlay at depth 2 draws over all of that. The banner behind the game-over message is at depth 3, and the text is at depth 4, keeping it readable.


2.8.5 The banner and text
this.add.rectangle(W / 2, H / 2, 360, 90, color, 1).setDepth(3);
this.add.text(W / 2, H / 2 - 8, message, { ... }).setOrigin(0.5).setDepth(4);
this.add.text(W / 2, H / 2 + 22, 'press R to restart', { ... }).setOrigin(0.5).setDepth(4);
A centered 360×90 rectangle in the end-game color (green for win, red for loss), then two text objects stacked on top of it: the big message eight pixels above center, and the restart hint 22 pixels below. Both use setOrigin(0.5) — the default origin is the top-left corner, which would misalign them; anchoring at the center lets us position by the logical midpoint.
Notice all of this is done in one burst and never updated afterward. The overlay is a one-shot render — it appears once when the game ends and stays put until scene.restart() wipes the entire scene.

2.9 What update() looks like now
update() {
  if (Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.rKey)) {
    this.scene.restart();
    return;
  }

  if (this.gameOver) return;

  // ... normal input & movement ...
}
Two guard clauses at the top, then the usual Chapter 1 logic. This is a common idiom: guard clauses handle the exceptional paths first, returning early, so the normal flow reads cleanly without being wrapped in nested ifs.
Reading top to bottom:

If R was just pressed, restart and stop. Nothing else matters this frame.
If the game is over (and R was not pressed), do nothing. Let the physics-paused world sit.
Otherwise, play the game as usual — read input, set velocities, handle jumping.

A.3 Objects
An object is an unordered collection of key-value pairs called properties. It is one of JavaScript’s most fundamental structures — and one of the most-used in the game.

Object literals
You create an object by writing its contents between {}. Each entry is key: value, and entries are separated by commas.
const config = {
  type: Phaser.AUTO,
  width: 800,
  height: 500,
  backgroundColor: '#040434',
  physics: {
    default: 'arcade',
    arcade: { gravity: { y: 600 }, debug: false }
  },
  scene: [GameScene]
};
This is the configuration object passed to new Phaser.Game(config) in main.js. Phaser reads it to know the canvas size, which physics engine to use, how strong gravity should be, and which scenes to register.


Accessing properties
Use dot notation to reach a property:
config.width               // 800
config.physics             // { default: 'arcade', arcade: { ... } }
config.physics.default     // 'arcade'
Chain dots to reach nested properties:
config.physics.arcade.gravity.y   // 600


Objects vs classes
An object literal is just data — it has no associated behavior. The config object is a plain container. Classes (covered in [A.6]) are blueprints that bundle data and methods together, and they produce objects with a specific prototype. The distinction: a config object is a bag of values; a GameScene instance is a live, behavior-rich object.

Quiz: Nested property access
Given the config object from main.js:
const config = {
  width: 800,
  physics: {
    default: 'arcade',
    arcade: { gravity: { y: 600 }, debug: false }
  }
};
What does config.physics.arcade.gravity.y evaluate to?

 undefined — you can’t chain dots across multiple nested objects.  600  { y: 600 } — the dots stop at the innermost object, they don’t unwrap primitive values.  A ReferenceError, because gravity isn’t declared as a variable. Check Answer

A.5 Functions
A function is a reusable block of code. You define it once and call it whenever you need it.
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}

add(3, 4);   // 7

Parameters and return values
Functions receive inputs as parameters (the names listed in the definition) and can send back an output with return.
function describe(key, w, h) {
  return key + ' is ' + w + '×' + h;
}

describe('ground', 800, 32);   // 'ground is 800×32'
If a function has no return statement, it implicitly returns undefined.


Arrow functions
ES6 (2015) introduced a shorter function syntax using =&gt;:
// Traditional function expression
const add = function(a, b) { return a + b; };

// Arrow function — same behavior, shorter syntax
const add = (a, b) =&gt; { return a + b; };

// Even shorter when the body is a single expression (implicit return)
const add = (a, b) =&gt; a + b;
Arrow functions appear in the game wherever a short callback is needed inline:
this.physics.add.overlap(this.player, this.coins, (_player, coin) =&gt; {
  coin.destroy();
  this.score++;
  this.scoreText.setText('Score: ' + this.score);
});
The function (_player, coin) =&gt; { ... } is written inline and passed directly to overlap. It is never given a name — it doesn’t need one because it is used in only this one place.






NoteThe underscore parameter prefix



_player uses a leading underscore to signal that the first argument is intentionally not used. The overlap callback always receives two arguments (the two overlapping objects). Here only coin is needed; _player is ignored. The underscore is a convention, not syntax — JavaScript doesn’t enforce it, but readers (and linters) understand it to mean “I know this parameter exists; I’m deliberately leaving it unused.”




Arrow functions and this
Arrow functions have one critical behavioral difference from regular functions: they do not create their own this. Instead, they capture this from the surrounding scope — the enclosing method they are written inside.
This matters in the overlap callback:
// Inside create() — a class method where `this` is the scene instance
this.physics.add.overlap(this.player, this.coins, (_player, coin) =&gt; {
  coin.destroy();
  this.score++;           // `this` here is the scene — correct
  this.scoreText.setText('Score: ' + this.score);
});
If the same code used a regular function keyword instead:
this.physics.add.overlap(this.player, this.coins, function(_player, coin) {
  this.score++;   // `this` is wrong here — not the scene
});
When Phaser calls a regular function callback, this inside that function is no longer the scene — it’s whatever Phaser’s internal code sets it to (usually undefined in strict mode). The arrow function avoids this completely by locking this to the value it had when create() was running.
This is the most common source of bugs for developers moving into class-based JavaScript. Arrow functions in callbacks are the idiomatic solution.

Quiz: Arrow function this
What is the single most important behavioral difference between a traditional function(...) { ... } and an arrow (...) =&gt; { ... } that makes arrow functions the right choice for the overlap callback in create()?

 Arrow functions can access closure variables, while traditional functions cannot.  Arrow functions are measurably faster at runtime, which matters for callbacks that fire every frame.  Arrow functions do not have their own this — they inherit it from the enclosing scope at definition time. Written inside create(), the arrow function’s this is locked to the scene instance, so this.score inside the callback still refers to the scene even though Phaser invokes the callback later from a different context.  Arrow functions can be passed to Phaser APIs; traditional functions cannot. Check Answer

A.6 Classes and Object-Oriented Programming
This is the most important concept in the book. The entire game lives inside a class. Understanding classes unlocks everything else.

The problem classes solve
Imagine writing the game without classes. You’d have a loose collection of variables:
let playerX = 100;
let playerY = 420;
let playerScore = 0;
let enemyX = 440;
let enemyY = 227;
And a collection of functions that operate on them:
function movePlayerLeft()  { playerX -= 220; }
function movePlayerRight() { playerX += 220; }
function killEnemy()       { enemyX = -9999; }
This works for a tiny program. But the moment you want two players or five enemies, it falls apart — there’s no structure to say which variables belong to which object. How do you give each enemy its own x position? How do you copy state? How do you prevent a function for one enemy from accidentally touching another’s data?
Classes solve this by bundling related data and behavior into a single unit. Each instance of the class is its own self-contained object with its own copy of the data.


Class syntax
class GameScene extends Phaser.Scene {
  constructor() {
    super({ key: 'GameScene' });
  }

  create()  { ... }
  update()  { ... }
  genRect(key, w, h, color) { ... }
}







Keyword
Role




class
Declares the class


GameScene
The class name — PascalCase by convention


extends Phaser.Scene
Inherits everything from Phaser.Scene


constructor()
Runs once when the class is instantiated with new


super()
Calls the parent class constructor


Method definitions
Functions that belong to every instance





new — creating an instance
A class is a blueprint, not an object. To create an actual object from the blueprint, you use the new keyword:
new Phaser.Game(config);
This creates a new Phaser.Game instance. What new does internally:

Creates a fresh empty object
Links it to Phaser.Game’s prototype
Runs the Phaser.Game constructor with the arguments you provided
Returns the new object

You usually store the result in a variable. For Phaser.Game, you typically don’t — starting the game is a one-time side effect, and you don’t need to reference the game object afterward.
Phaser does the same thing with your GameScene:
const scene = new GameScene();   // Phaser does this internally
Each new call creates an independent instance with its own data.


Instance properties and this
Inside a class method, this refers to the specific instance the method was called on. When create() runs and you write:
this.player = this.physics.add.sprite(100, H - 80, 'player');
this.score  = 0;
this.gameOver = false;
You are attaching properties to this particular scene instance. They persist for the lifetime of the instance. That’s why this.score set in create() is still readable in update() 60 frames later — it lives on the instance, not inside any single method call.
If you had two separate GameScene instances, each would have its own this.player, its own this.score, its own this.gameOver, completely independent of the other.


Methods
Methods are functions defined inside a class body. They have automatic access to this:
class GameScene extends Phaser.Scene {
  genRect(key, w, h, color) {
    const g = this.make.graphics({ add: false });  // `this` works here
    g.fillStyle(color);
    g.fillRect(0, 0, w, h);
    g.generateTexture(key, w, h);
    g.destroy();
  }
}
You call it from another method as this.genRect('ground', W, 32, 0x4caf50), and this is automatically the scene instance.
Notice there is no function keyword inside a class body — method definitions use the shorthand syntax:
methodName(param1, param2) {
  // body
}


Inheritance: extends and super
Inheritance lets one class build on another. In the game:
export default class GameScene extends Phaser.Scene {
GameScene is a subclass of Phaser.Scene. It inherits everything Phaser.Scene already has: the lifecycle system, this.physics, this.add, this.input, this.cameras, this.tweens, and all the rest. Without extends Phaser.Scene, none of those would exist on this, and every line that uses them would throw a TypeError.
Think of it as specialization: Phaser.Scene is a general-purpose scene engine. GameScene is a specific kind of scene — one that knows how to build this particular game level.
super() calls the parent class constructor. In a subclass, you must call super() before accessing this. If you forget:
constructor() {
  this.score = 0;                // ReferenceError: Must call super constructor first
  super({ key: 'GameScene' });
}
JavaScript enforces this because the parent constructor needs to run first to set up the object foundation. super({ key: 'GameScene' }) passes the scene’s name up to Phaser.Scene’s constructor, which registers it internally.

Quiz: Classes and super()
In the GameScene constructor below, you decide to remove the super() call to clean things up:
constructor() {
  // super({ key: 'GameScene' });   ← removed
}
What happens when Phaser tries to instantiate GameScene?

 Nothing special — super() is optional inside class constructors.  The scene still runs, but it has no name so other scenes can’t reference it by key.  JavaScript throws a ReferenceError — in a subclass, you must call super() before you can access this, and the engine enforces this before the constructor body finishes. Phaser never even gets to create().  Only create() breaks; update() still runs as long as no scene code uses this.physics. Check Answer







How Phaser uses your methods
When Phaser launches a scene, it effectively does this:
const scene = new GameScene();

scene.create();              // called once when the scene starts
scene.update(time, delta);   // called every frame
If you define create() in your class, Phaser calls it. If you don’t, Phaser skips it silently — no error. The same for update() and preload(). This is why those three method names are significant: Phaser looks for them by name on your scene instance.
Methods you define with any other name — like genRect or _endGame — Phaser never calls on its own. You call them yourself from within create() or update().


When you’d have more classes
Our game has only GameScene, but a more developed game typically has several classes. Some extend Phaser classes; others are plain JavaScript objects.
Additional scene classes are the most common:
class BootScene   extends Phaser.Scene { }  // shows a logo while assets load
class MenuScene   extends Phaser.Scene { }  // title screen, play button
class GameScene   extends Phaser.Scene { }  // the level
class GameOver    extends Phaser.Scene { }  // death screen, score, retry button
Custom game object classes let enemies, projectiles, and pickups carry their own logic:
class Enemy extends Phaser.GameObjects.Sprite {
  constructor(scene, x, y) {
    super(scene, x, y, 'enemy');
    this.health = 3;
    this.speed  = 80;
  }
  takeDamage() {
    this.health--;
    if (this.health &lt;= 0) this.destroy();
  }
}
Because Enemy extends a Phaser sprite class, it is a real Phaser sprite — with physics, animations, and all normal sprite properties — plus whatever custom behavior you add.
Plain helper classes handle logic with no Phaser dependency:
class ScoreManager {
  constructor() { this.score = 0; this.highScore = 0; }
  add(points) { this.score += points; }
  save() { localStorage.setItem('highScore', this.score); }
}
No extends, no Phaser. Just a clean bundle of related state and behavior. You’d instantiate it in create() and store it as this.scoreManager.


The underscore convention: “private” methods
_endGame(message, color) { ... }
The leading underscore is a naming convention, not a language rule. It signals: “this is an internal implementation detail — don’t call it from outside this class.” It’s a message to other programmers (and your future self).
JavaScript does have truly private methods using #:
#endGame(message, color) { ... }
this.#endGame('You Win!', 0x2e7d32);   // works inside the class
// scene.#endGame(...)                  // SyntaxError if called from outside
Private # methods are enforced by the engine. The underscore convention is softer and more common in Phaser codebases — both communicate the same intent.

A.7 this in Depth
this is one of JavaScript’s most frequently misunderstood features. It appears constantly in the game code, and understanding it clearly removes a whole class of potential bugs.

The core rule for class methods
Inside a class method, this is the instance the method was called on:
class GameScene extends Phaser.Scene {
  create() {
    this.score = 0;   // `this` = the GameScene instance
  }
  update() {
    this.score++;     // same `this` — the same instance, still alive
  }
}
When Phaser calls scene.create(), JavaScript sets this to scene for the duration of that call. Same for every subsequent update() call.


Properties set in one method are available in all others
Because all methods share the same this, a property written in create():
this.player = this.physics.add.sprite(100, H - 80, 'player');
…is readable in update():
const body = this.player.body;   // same property, same instance
And in helper methods:
_endGame(message, color) {
  this.physics.pause();   // `this` is still the scene instance
}
This is the glue that holds the whole class together. Without this, each method would be isolated with no way to share state.


When this goes wrong
The problem arises when a function is called in a context where this isn’t set to what you expect. The most common case is passing a method as a callback:
// WRONG: passing a method as a callback
const fn = this.someMethod;   // detaches `this`
fn();                         // `this` inside someMethod is now undefined
And specifically with regular function callbacks passed to Phaser:
// WRONG: regular function loses `this`
this.physics.add.overlap(a, b, function() {
  this.score++;   // TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined
});

// CORRECT: arrow function captures `this` from the enclosing scope
this.physics.add.overlap(a, b, () =&gt; {
  this.score++;   // works — `this` is the scene
});
The rule: use arrow functions for any callback written inside a class method. Arrow functions don’t have their own this; they inherit it from the enclosing scope at the moment they are written. That scope is create(), where this is the scene instance — exactly what you want.

Quiz: When this goes wrong
Consider this fragment from create(). What actually happens when the player overlaps a coin?
// `const self = this;` is NOT used; no arrow function either.
this.physics.add.overlap(this.player, this.coins, function (_player, coin) {
  coin.destroy();
  this.score++;
  this.scoreText.setText('Score: ' + this.score);
});

 It works identically — there’s no functional difference between function and =&gt; for callbacks.  The coin is destroyed (because coin is a parameter, not this), but then this.score++ throws a TypeError — inside a regular function callback, this is not the scene (usually undefined in strict mode), so this.score can’t be read.  The overlap callback never fires because Phaser only accepts arrow functions.  The score text updates correctly, but the coin fails to destroy because coin inside a function is undefined. Check Answer

A.9 Control Flow

if, else if, else
if (left)       body.setVelocityX(-220);
else if (right) body.setVelocityX(220);
else            body.setVelocityX(0);
Reading this: if the player is pressing left, set negative x velocity; if pressing right instead, set positive x velocity; otherwise (no direction key held), zero the velocity to stop movement.
When the branch body is a single statement, curly braces {} are optional. When it’s more than one line, they are required.


Guard clauses
A guard clause is an early return that handles a special case at the top of a function, before the main logic runs:
update() {
  if (Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.rKey)) {
    this.scene.restart();
    return;            // exit immediately — nothing else matters this frame
  }

  if (this.gameOver) return;   // game is over — skip all normal logic

  // Normal logic runs only when neither guard has triggered
  const body    = this.player.body;
  const onFloor = body.blocked.down;
  // ...
}
Guard clauses are the idiomatic alternative to deeply nested if blocks. Without them, the same logic would look like:
update() {
  if (!Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.rKey)) {
    if (!this.gameOver) {
      // normal logic buried two levels deep
    }
  }
}
Guards keep the normal path readable by disposing of the exceptional cases first.


Logical operators
|| (OR): True if at least one operand is truthy.
const left = this.cursors.left.isDown || this.wasd.left.isDown;
The player moves left if the left arrow key OR the A key is held — either one is enough.
&& (AND): True only when both operands are truthy.
if (jump && onFloor) body.setVelocityY(-550);
Jump only if the jump key was just pressed AND the player is currently on the ground.
Short-circuit evaluation: JavaScript stops evaluating an || expression as soon as it finds a truthy value, and stops evaluating && as soon as it finds a falsy one. If this.cursors.left.isDown is true, JavaScript never evaluates this.wasd.left.isDown — it already has its answer.


Strict equality: ===
JavaScript has two equality operators:







Operator
Behavior




==
Loose equality — converts types before comparing. '5' == 5 is true.


===
Strict equality — no type conversion. '5' === 5 is false.



Always use ===. Loose equality produces counterintuitive results:
''   == false     // true (!)
0    == false     // true (!)
null == undefined // true (!)
The game uses === for the win check:
if (this.score === this.totalCoins) {
  this._endGame('You Win!', 0x2e7d32);
}
Both values are numbers, so == would happen to work here too. Use === anyway — it’s the safe default.


Increment and compound assignment
this.score++;        // equivalent to: this.score = this.score + 1
this.score += 5;     // equivalent to: this.score = this.score + 5
++ appears every time a coin is collected. += is useful when the increment isn’t exactly 1.

Quiz: Guard clauses and strict equality
In Chapter 2, the coin overlap callback starts with if (this.gameOver) return; and the win check uses this.score === this.totalCoins. Which statement correctly describes these two patterns?

 The if (this.gameOver) return; is a loop break; the === is identical in behavior to == for numbers.  if (this.gameOver) return; is a guard clause — an early exit that keeps the “normal” path of the callback un-nested. === is strict equality (no type coercion); using it consistently is the safe default because == can produce surprising results like 0 == false being true.  return; inside an arrow function has no effect; it only works in traditional function declarations.  === compares object identity, which is why it’s used to check if two scores are the same — numbers are objects in JavaScript. Check Answer

A.10 Callbacks
A callback is a function passed as an argument to another function, to be called later.
This pattern appears everywhere in Phaser:
// You write:
this.physics.add.overlap(this.player, this.coins, (_player, coin) =&gt; {
  coin.destroy();
  this.score++;
  this.scoreText.setText('Score: ' + this.score);
});

// Phaser stores the callback internally.
// Every frame, during the physics step, Phaser checks for overlaps.
// When it finds one, it calls your function with the overlapping objects:
yourCallback(playerObject, coinObject);
You are not calling the callback directly. You are handing it to Phaser, and Phaser calls it for you at the right moment — with the right arguments — from deep inside its physics step.
This is the same pattern across all Phaser event APIs:







Phaser API call
When your callback fires




physics.add.overlap(a, b, fn)
Every frame an overlap is detected between a and b


physics.add.collider(a, b, fn)
Every frame a collision is resolved between a and b


tweens.add({ onComplete: fn })
When a tween finishes playing


input.keyboard.on('keydown', fn)
When any key is pressed



You declare the relationship (“when these overlap, do this”) and Phaser manages the timing entirely.

Idempotent guards in callbacks
In Chapter 2, the coin callback has an extra guard:
this.physics.add.overlap(this.player, this.coins, (_player, coin) =&gt; {
  if (this.gameOver) return;   // ← early exit if game already ended
  coin.destroy();
  // ...
});
And _endGame has one too:
_endGame(message, color) {
  if (this.gameOver) return;   // ← early exit if already called
  this.gameOver = true;
  // ...
}
Both are examples of making a function idempotent — safe to call more than once, always producing the same result. The physics engine may fire overlap callbacks multiple times in rapid succession (including on the same frame that the game ends). Guards like these prevent double-triggering.

Quiz: When does a registered callback actually run?
When create() executes this.physics.add.overlap(a, b, myCallback), when does Phaser actually call myCallback?

 Once, immediately, the moment physics.add.overlap is called — Phaser runs the callback up-front and stores the result.  Every frame during Phaser’s physics step, but only if a and b are actually overlapping on that frame. Phaser stores the function and invokes it at the right moment in each tick. Your code never calls it directly.  Every frame no matter what — once the callback is registered, it runs 60 times per second regardless of any overlap.  Only when the user presses a key — overlaps are resolved in response to input events. Check Answer

Putting it all together
Here is a condensed version of GameScene.js with annotations linking every line back to a section in this appendix:
import * as Phaser from 'phaser';      // [A.8] namespace import

export default class GameScene         // [A.6] class, [A.8] default export
  extends Phaser.Scene {               // [A.6] inheritance

  constructor() {
    super({ key: 'GameScene' });        // [A.6] super() — required, [A.3] object literal
  }

  create() {
    const W = this.scale.width;         // [A.2] const, [A.6] this
    const H = this.scale.height;        // [A.1] numbers

    this.score    = 0;                  // [A.1] number, [A.6] instance property
    this.gameOver = false;              // [A.1] boolean, [A.6] instance property

    // ... textures, ground, platforms ...

    this.player = this.physics.add.sprite(100, H - 80, 'player');

    this.physics.add.overlap(          // [A.10] callback registration
      this.player, this.coins,
      (_player, coin) =&gt; {             // [A.5] arrow function, [A.7] captures `this`
        if (this.gameOver) return;     // [A.9] guard clause
        coin.destroy();
        this.score++;                  // [A.9] ++
        if (this.score === this.totalCoins) {   // [A.9] ===
          this._endGame('You Win!', 0x2e7d32);  // [A.6] method call, [A.1] hex color
        }
      }
    );
  }

  update() {
    if (this.gameOver) return;           // [A.9] guard clause

    const left = this.cursors.left.isDown || this.wasd.left.isDown;  // [A.9] ||
    const jump = Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.cursors.up)
              || Phaser.Input.Keyboard.JustDown(this.cursors.space);

    if (left)       this.player.body.setVelocityX(-220); // [A.9] if/else
    else if (right) this.player.body.setVelocityX(220);
    else            this.player.body.setVelocityX(0);

    if (jump && this.player.body.blocked.down)   // [A.9] &&
      this.player.body.setVelocityY(-550);
  }

  _endGame(message, color) {            // [A.6] underscore = private by convention
    if (this.gameOver) return;          // [A.10] idempotent guard
    this.gameOver = true;
    this.physics.pause();
    this.tweens.killAll();
    // ... overlay rendering ...
  }

  genRect(key, w, h, color) {           // [A.5] method with parameters
    const g = this.make.graphics({ add: false });  // [A.3] object literal
    g.fillStyle(color);
    g.fillRect(0, 0, w, h);
    g.generateTexture(key, w, h);
    g.destroy();
  }
}
Every line of game code uses one or more of the concepts above. As you read Chapter 1 and Chapter 2, come back here whenever the JavaScript itself — not the Phaser API — is the part that needs unpacking.
